Here's the complete migration with key pitfalls explained:

## ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) — Migrated Code

```csharp
// ReportController.cs
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // PITFALL 1: No more event-driven postbacks. Web Forms' btnExport_Click
    // becomes an action method. Use [HttpPost] for form submissions.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // PITFALL 2: Response.Clear(), Response.Write(), Response.End() are GONE.
        // Response.End() threw ThreadAbortException internally — this entire
        // pattern is eliminated. Return a FileResult instead.
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"  // sets Content-Disposition automatically
        );
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Redirect()
    {
        // User.Identity works the same way (via middleware now, not modules)
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // PITFALL 3: Response.Redirect("/login", true) called Thread.Abort()
            // to stop execution. In ASP.NET Core, RedirectToAction/Redirect
            // simply returns a 302 result — no exception, no thread abort.
            // Execution continues AFTER this return, so you MUST return.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // PITFALL 4: Remove ALL ThreadAbortException catches.
        // They will NEVER fire in .NET Core — Thread.Abort() throws
        // PlatformNotSupportedException. This catch block would silently
        // swallow real errors if the exception type ever matched.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() => /* your logic */;
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* your logic */ }
    private void LogError(Exception ex) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls Summary

| # | .NET Framework Pattern | .NET 8 Replacement | Trap |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | `Response.End()` | Return `IActionResult` | `Response.End()` doesn't exist. Code after it **will execute** if you try to mimic it. |
| 2 | `Response.Write(data)` | `File()` / `Content()` | Writing directly to the response stream bypasses filters and content negotiation. |
| 3 | `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `return Redirect(url)` | The old `endResponse:true` aborted the thread. Now you **must** `return` — otherwise the method keeps running. |
| 4 | `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | **Delete it** | `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET Core. These catch blocks are dead code — or worse, they mask bugs if you catch `Exception` broadly. |
| 5 | `Response.AddHeader()` | Built into `File()` | Or use `Response.Headers.Append()` if manual control is needed. |

## Startup Wiring (Program.cs)

```csharp
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

builder.Services.AddControllersWithViews();
builder.Services.AddAuthentication(/* your scheme */);

var app = builder.Build();

app.UseAuthentication();  // replaces FormsAuthenticationModule
app.UseAuthorization();
app.MapControllerRoute("default", "{controller=Home}/{action=Index}/{id?}");

app.Run();
```

**The single biggest trap**: in Framework, `Response.Redirect(url, true)` and `Response.End()` halted execution via `Thread.Abort()`. In .NET 8, nothing stops execution — if you forget to `return` the `IActionResult`, your method runs to completion and you'll get double-response errors or silent logic bugs.
